    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Utensils having a handle and a concave, blunt pushing surface designed for use by toddlers to push food onto their forks or spoons. Popular in the 19th and early 20th century, often collected in a set with a pap spoon, baby spoon, and a baby fork.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000053038/Making the Most of Spoons  (1917)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Utensilio consistente en un rectángulo plano y vertical añadido a un mango. Es utilizado por los niños para empujar la comida hacia sus tenedores y cucharas.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Keukengerei dat bestaat uit een platte, verticale rechthoek die aan een handvat vastzit en door kinderen wordt gebruikt om voedsel op hun vork of lepel te duwen.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>具有一支把手和一個凹下、不銳利之推進面的器皿，供幼童用來將食物推至其叉子或湯匙。流行於西元十九世紀與二十世紀初期，常與粥匙、嬰兒匙和嬰兒叉搭配成套。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
